`Years later`, he grew into a noble and `wise` young man. The wife of his master tried to `tempt` him into sin, but Yusuf refused, choosing `obedience to` Allah over worldly desire. Because of false `accusations`, he was sent to prison.

Even in prison, Yusuf did not lose hope. He helped other prisoners and `interpreted` their dreams with `wisdom`. One day, the king of Egypt had a `troubling` dream. No one could explain it — except Yusuf.

Yusuf interpreted the dream: seven years of `abundance` would be followed by seven years of `famine`. He advised the king to store `grain` during the good years. Impressed by his wisdom and honesty, the king `freed` Yusuf and made him a high official `in charge` of the country’s food supply.

